g.text: gpu array storing vertex data for each shape
The GPU array is a dynamic array that is updated once a particular
queue is full in the shape manager or when a draw call is issued and
When copying a shape to GPU memory, we just copy the vertex data,
and store the begin and end indices into the shape.
Later on when we need to modify/edit the shape, we do so by first clearing
the shape and then adding new vertices. If the vertex data of selected shape is between
the vertex data of two different shapes, we need to reshuffle the shapes data such that
the new shape data is shifted to end of buffer and the blank space in between is filled
by shifting all vertex data and updating begin and end indices of selected arrays
Instead of storing shape data in a single UBO, we'll create separate UBOs
for each shape. Since we know that we'll use only one shape in a single
vkCmdDraw call, we actually need to pass only one shape.
This eases the design dramatically where each shape has it's own DeviceBuffer object,
and we don't need the complex (begin, end) design like here
